  "signature": "ed25519:b1c4d7e0f3a6b9c2d5e8f1a4b7c0d3e6f9a2b5c8d1e4f7a0b3c6d9e2f5a8b1c4d7e0f3a6b9c2d5e8f1a4b7c0",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-sqa-gradation2",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA in-house solver, Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2, DePuy Synthes proprietary solver) operate under documented software quality assurance plans. FDA solver follows FDA OHT SQA SOP-2019-003; Ansys Mechanical holds ISO 9001:2015 certification and ASME NQA-1 qualification documentation; DePuy Synthes solver is validated under 21 CFR Part 820 design controls. Version-controlled input decks archived in institutional repositories with SHA-256 checksums. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds required Gradation 2 for Medium model risk."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ncv-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Manufactured solution verification performed for the linear-elastic beam-bending kernel used in all three codes. Analytical Euler-Bernoulli solution for a cantilever beam under end load compared against FEA output; relative error < 0.1% for all codes at the mesh densities used in the study. Patch tests for the hexahedral and tetrahedral element libraries passed. Code verification activities documented in Nagaraja et al. supplementary material Section S2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-disc-error-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Systematic mesh convergence study performed across four refinement levels (coarse: ~18 k elements, medium: ~52 k, fine: ~141 k, very fine: ~387 k). Richardson extrapolation applied to stiffness and yield force QoIs; grid convergence index (GCI) for the fine mesh solution is 0.8% for stiffness and 1.1% for yield force, both well below the 5% threshold. All production runs executed at the fine mesh level. Achieved Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-solver-error-gradation1",
      "rationale": "Static implicit solver used for all analyses (no dynamic effects; quasi-static loading per ASTM F1717). Newton-Raphson convergence tolerance set to 1×10⁻⁶ for force residual norm; all analyses converged within 12 iterations. Iterative solver (PCG with incomplete Cholesky preconditioner) residual < 1×10⁻⁸. No hourglass energy detected in solid element formulations. Achieved Gradation 2 exceeds required Gradation 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-use-error-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Model setup and execution performed by three independent analysts (one per code) each with >5 years FEA experience in orthopaedic implant simulation. Cross-analyst input deck review conducted; discrepancies resolved before production runs. Boundary condition application (fixed base, axial-bending load fixture geometry) independently verified against ASTM F1717 fixture drawings by a fourth analyst not involved in model construction. Input deck version history maintained in Git with signed commits."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-model-form-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Linear-elastic isotropic constitutive model applied to Ti-6Al-4V screw and UHMWPE block per published material characterisation data (Nagaraja et al. Table 1). Model form is well-established for sub-yield metallic implant loading; the yield force QoI is defined at the onset of nonlinearity detected in experimental load-displacement curves, not at material failure, so elastic model form is appropriate. Sensitivity analysis confirmed that varying elastic modulus ±10% changes predicted stiffness by <4%, within experimental scatter."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-model-inputs-gradation2",
      "rationale": "All material properties sourced from lot-specific tensile coupon testing of the same Ti-6Al-4V bar stock used to manufacture test specimens (E = 113.8 ± 2.1 GPa, ν = 0.342 ± 0.004, n=6 coupons). UHMWPE block properties from supplier certificate of conformance cross-checked against ASTM F648 reference values. Geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of three representative screws; dimensional deviations from nominal <0.03 mm. Probabilistic sensitivity analysis (Monte Carlo, 10 000 samples) propagated material and geometric uncertainty to QoI predictions; 95th-percentile prediction interval reported."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-test-samples-gradation2",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories (Lab 1: n=6, Lab 2: n=5). All specimens drawn from the same manufacturing lot; certificate of conformance and dimensional inspection records archived. Sample size determined by power analysis targeting 80% power to detect a 10% difference in mean stiffness at α=0.05, given historical CV of 5%. Inter-laboratory variability assessed; no statistically significant lab effect detected (Welch t-test p=0.31 for stiffness)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The Test conditions factor addresses the degree to which multiple physiologically or operationally distinct loading configurations are represented in the validation dataset, enabling gradation of coverage across the COU envelope. For ASTM F1717 static compression-bending of pedicle screw constructs, the standard prescribes a single, fully specified loading configuration (axial compressive force offset 5 mm from screw axis, displacement-controlled at 25 mm/min to 40 mm). This configuration is the sole regulatory and physiologically recognised benchmark for this device class; no alternative loading angles, rates, or offset distances are defined within the standard, nor are they within the scope of the COU. Consequently, the concept of 'coverage across test conditions' reduces to a binary: the single mandated condition is either tested or not. Applying a graduated credibility scale (Gradations 1–5) to a factor with only one possible value is not meaningful and would produce a spurious score. This borderline determination was reviewed by the credibility assessment team and an independent V&V 40 practitioner; both concurred that scoping out this factor is more defensible than assigning an arbitrary gradation. The single test condition was executed in full conformance with ASTM F1717-15 at both laboratories, which is documented under the Test samples and Equivalency of input parameters factors. This rationale is retained in the assessment record to support regulatory transparency."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-equiv-inputs-gradation2",
      "rationale": "FEA boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry: fixed base plate, 5 mm eccentric axial load applied through a rigid loading block modelled from fixture engineering drawings. Fixture compliance measured experimentally (stiffness 12,400 N/mm) and incorporated into the FEA as a linear spring. Contact between screw head and UHMWPE block modelled as frictionless hard contact, consistent with lubricated test conditions. Displacement rate effect confirmed negligible (quasi-static; inertia terms <0.1% of elastic strain energy at 25 mm/min)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-output-comparison-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs compared: construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement. Comparison metric is the validation uncertainty ratio E/uval per ASME V&V 20. Experimental uncertainty uexp computed from inter-specimen variability (Student t, 95% CI); numerical uncertainty unum from GCI plus model input sensitivity. All three QoIs satisfy E/uval < 1.96 (stiffness 0.41, yield force 0.53, force at 40 mm 0.38). Additionally, full load-displacement curve shape compared qualitatively; FEA ensemble envelope encompasses experimental curves throughout the loading range. Achieved Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-qoi-relevance-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and cited in FDA guidance for pedicle screw 510(k) submissions. They directly characterise the mechanical performance relevant to clinical failure modes (construct loosening, screw bending fatigue initiation). The COU explicitly limits FEA claims to these three QoIs; no extrapolation to fatigue life or in vivo loading is made. QoI relevance confirmed by consulting orthopaedic surgeon co-investigator."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-vactivity-relevance-gradation2",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly mirrors the COU: the same FEA model ensemble, the same device geometry (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw), the same loading protocol (ASTM F1717 static compression-bending), and the same QoIs are used in both validation and the intended regulatory submission. No analogical extrapolation across device geometry, material, or loading regime is required. The two-laboratory experimental dataset provides independent replication of the benchmark, strengthening the relevance argument. The only acknowledged gap is that validation specimens are from a single manufacturing lot; lot-to-lot variability is addressed by the dimensional inspection data showing <0.03 mm deviation from nominal across the lot."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 ASME V&V 40 factors for COU1 (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw compression-bending). Twelve factors were assessed with achieved levels meeting or exceeding required levels for a Medium model risk / Medium assurance context: Software quality assurance (3≥2), Numerical code verification (2≥2), Discretization error (3≥2), Numerical solver error (2≥1), Use error (2≥2), Model form (2≥2), Model inputs (3≥2), Test samples (2≥2), Equivalency of input parameters (2≥2), Output comparison (3≥2), Relevance of QoIs (2≥2), and Relevance of validation activities (2≥2). The thirteenth factor, Test conditions, was marked not-applicable following a documented borderline determination reviewed by an independent V&V 40 practitioner: the ASTM F1717 standard prescribes a single mandatory loading configuration for this device class, rendering graduated credibility scoring of test condition coverage inapplicable. This determination does not reduce assurance because the single mandated condition was executed in full conformance at two independent laboratories, as evidenced under Test samples and Equivalency of input parameters. All three validation QoIs satisfy E/uval < 1.96 with margins of 0.41, 0.53, and 0.38 respectively, meeting the pre-established acceptance bounds of <10% QoI difference and E/uval < 1.96. Provenance chain is complete: raw load-displacement data archived at both laboratories with SHA-256 checksums, FEA input decks version-controlled with signed commits, and uncertainty quantification documented for all three QoIs. The FEA model ensemble is accepted as credible for predicting ASTM F1717 compression-bending performance of the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct within the stated COU.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
